<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><p data-start="0" data-end="61" class="">Here are your refined notes with your explanation included:</p>
<hr data-start="63" data-end="66" class="" style="">
<h2 data-start="68" data-end="123" class=""><strong data-start="71" data-end="121">Recursive and Recursively Enumerable Languages</strong></h2>
<h3 data-start="125" data-end="179" class=""><strong data-start="129" data-end="177">1. Recursive Languages (Decidable Languages)</strong></h3>
<ul data-start="180" data-end="651">
<li data-start="180" data-end="341" class="" style="">
<p data-start="182" data-end="341" class="">A language <strong data-start="193" data-end="198">L</strong> is <strong data-start="202" data-end="215">recursive</strong> if there exists a <strong data-start="234" data-end="275">Turing Machine (TM) that always halts</strong> and correctly decides whether a string belongs to <strong data-start="326" data-end="331">L</strong> or not.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="342" data-end="541" class="" style="">
<p data-start="344" data-end="541" class="">It is called <strong data-start="357" data-end="377">Turing Decidable</strong> because for every string, the TM will either <strong data-start="423" data-end="433">accept</strong> (if the string is in L) or <strong data-start="461" data-end="471">reject</strong> (if the string is not in L), and it always <strong data-start="515" data-end="524">halts</strong> in both cases.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="542" data-end="651" class="" style="">
<p data-start="544" data-end="651" class="">Since the TM always <strong data-start="564" data-end="575">decides</strong> the membership of any input string, we call such languages <strong data-start="635" data-end="648">decidable</strong>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="653" data-end="734" class="">ðŸ”¹ <strong data-start="656" data-end="668">Example:</strong> <code data-start="669" data-end="732">{ w | w is a valid arithmetic expression and evaluates to 0 }</code></p>
<hr data-start="736" data-end="739lass="" style="">
<h3 data-start="741" data-end="791" class=""><strong data-start="745" data-end="789">2. Recursively Enumerable (RE) Languages</strong></h3>
<ul data-start="792" data-end="1399">
<li data-start="792" data-end="1057" class="" style="">
<p data-start="794" data-end="913" class="">A language <strong data-start="805" data-end="810">L</strong> is <strong data-start="814" data-end="845">recursively enumerable (RE)</strong> if there exists a <strong data-start="864" data-end="901">Turing Machine that recognizes it</strong>, meaning:</p>
<ul data-start="916" data-end="1057">
<li data-start="916" data-end="978" class="" style="">
<p data-start="918" data-end="978" class="">If a string <strong data-start="930" data-end="941">is in L</strong>, the TM <strong data-start="950" data-end="972">eventually accepts</strong> it.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="981" data-end="1057" class="" style="">
<p data-start="983" data-end="1057" class="">If a string <strong data-start="995" data-end="1010">is not in L</strong>, the TM <strong data-start="1019" data-end="1044">may loop indefinitely</strong> or reject.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li data-start="1058" data-end="1245" class="" style="">
<p data-start="1060" data-end="1245" class="">It is called <strong data-start="1073" data-end="1096">Turing Recognizable</strong> because the TM can <strong data-start="1116" data-end="1129">recognize</strong> valid strings by accepting them, but if a string is not in <strong data-start="1189" data-end="1194">L</strong>, it might <strong data-start="1205" data-end="1219">never halt</strong> (instead of rejecting).</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1246" data-end="1399" class="" style="">
<p data-start="1248" data-end="1399" class="">Since the TM <strong data-start="1261" data-end="1287">does not always decide</strong> the membership (it might run forever), we call such languages <strong data-start="1350" data-end="1396">recognizable but not necessarily decidable</strong>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1401" data-end="1506" class="">ðŸ”¹ <strong dattart="1404" data-end="1416">Example:</strong> <code data-start="1417" data-end="1461">{ w | w encodes a halting Turing Machine }</code> (Halting problem is RE but not recursive).</p>
<hr data-start="1508" data-end="1511" class="" style="">
<h3 data-start="1513" data-end="1538" class=""><strong data-start="1517" data-end="1536">Key Difference:</strong></h3>
<div class="overflow-x-auto contain-inline-size"><table data-start="1539" data-end="2153" data-is-only-node="" node="[object Object]"><thead data-start="1539" data-end="1613"><tr data-start="1539" data-end="1613"><th data-start="1539" data-end="1550">Feature</th><th data-start="1550" data-end="1578"><strong data-start="1552" data-end="1577">Recursive (Decidable)</strong></th><th data-start="1578" data-end="1613"><strong data-start="1580" data-end="1611">Recursively Enumerable (RE)</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody data-start="1686" data-end="2153"><tr data-start="1686" data-end="1740"><td><strong data-start="1688" data-end="1699">Halting</strong></td><td>Always halts</td><td>May loop indefinitely</td></tr><tr data-start="1741" data-end="1846"><td><strong data-start="1743" data-end="1757">Acceptance</strong></td><td>Accepts &amp; Rejects correctly</td><td>Accepts valid strings, but may not reject invalid ones</td></tr><tr data-start="1847" data-end="1911"><td><strong data-start="1849" data-end="1868">Turing Property</strong></td><td>Turing Decidable</td><td>Turing Recognizable</td></tr><tr data-start="1912" data-end="2052"><td><strong data-start="1914" data-end="1932">Why this name?</strong></td><td>It can <strong data-start="1942" data-end="1952">decide</strong> acceptance or rejection</td><td>It only <strong data-start="1987" data-end="2001">recognizes</strong> valid inputs but may not decide for invalid ones</td></tr><tr data-start="2053" data-end="2153"><td><strong data-start="2055" data-end="2075">Strict Inclusion</strong></td><td><strong data-start="2078" data-end="2096">Recursive âŠ‚ RE</strong> (All recursive languages are RE, but not vice versa)</td><td>td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>